==CONTENTS==
1. Basic Summary
2. Outward Personality
3. Hidden Personality
4. Good Targeting Topics
5. History (spoilers!)
6. Kyoko’s Gloves
7. Notable Special Markers
8. Trivia
===========

1. Basic Summary
- World-class (though not household-famous) homicide detective from Japan. Been in the business for 14 years, and she’s 19 years old.
- She actually carries a numerical rank of [910] in a registry of detectives in Japan. The numbers mean she’s a homicide detective, she specializes in “impossible” murders, and there are only about 20 detectives in the system ranked higher than her.
- Attended a prestigious high school (Hope’s Peak) that only accepts high school-age kids who are the best of the best in a certain field (like the Ultimate Mechanic, Ultimate Martial Artist, or Ultimate Pet Breeder).
- Her talent is that of the Ultimate Detective. She doesn’t say that she’s this or any detective unless prompted, though, so it’s up to you whether you want your character(s) to just already know or make a game out of trying to figure out just what her deal is.
- There are some markers for this; more on that below.

2. Outward Personality Traits
- Above all, crazy observant. Some characters may notice how she eyes every new person and room she sees up and down. Puts two and two together crazy fast.
- Starts a conversation as if it’s already underway. Super direct— never rude on purpose, but would rather just say what she’s thinking than be polite. Sometimes says the craziest shit, like directly asking about your fetishes, in the same breath she discusses yesterday’s weather, and in the exact same tone of voice. Is Social Anxiety’s sleep paralysis demon.
- More casual in her speech than Wikipe-tan, more clinical than…almost everyone else.
- Has an icy stare she maintains almost the whole game, and hard to get much of a reaction out of (even when gimmick situations happen). She does react, just…not much. Many may be wigged out.
- Acts a little detached. Losing doesn’t bother her, like, at all, but she enjoys herself in the game and performs just enough competitiveness to keep the mood alive.
- Sexually dominant later in the game. Bi-curious to start, has an attraction to women she explores openly without reservation.

3. Not-So-Outward Personality/Other Traits
- Values the truth above all else, even if it’s ugly.
- Not afraid to admit she’s a horny bastard like the rest of us, but she won’t go out of her way to do it either.
- Actually easygoing in her own odd way. She’s seen some serious shit in her time, so she’s able to take almost anyone or anything at face value as long as they’re being truthful and not hurting anybody.
- Just trying to relax and have fun with the game. Her idea of having fun isn’t weird, but she sure is!
- General likes: Coffee (has been taking it black since middle school), chocolate, cereal, hair braids, flowers, cute or pretty things.
- General dislikes: Goya fruit, cilantro, instant ramen, gambling for money.
- Has been overseas (incl. the USA, Canada, Germany, Switzerland, and more) for most of her life that she can remember; Japanese aesthetics and traditions are a rarity to her that she appreciates.
- People she likes: Heroes in general and people like her, sure, but even moreso openly-emotional or even stupid people who are good of heart.
- People she dislikes: People who try to hide the truth for selfish reasons, and generally most villains.
- Exists in a “real” world that had most of the same real-life pop culture as our world up to the year 2011. She’s familiar with real-life detective fiction.
- Kyoko is good with a gun. Specifically, she used a modded Remington M700 sniper rifle at age 13, and practiced with it so diligently she even slept holding it. If your character has a gun that exists in the real world, she can identify it by name.
- Also pretty good at hand-to-hand self-defense; not better than most trained fighers, but enough to defend herself against way higher weight classes. Trained by her other grandpa, multi-martial-art master Tohachiro Uzuchi.
- She has about no experience with magic or the supernatural (other than a self-proclaimed clairvoyant with little credibility as such) in her source material, with one major exception. She claims she can “hear the footsteps of the god of death as he moves” and has some apparent ability to sense when someone is going to die or attempt to kill another person. Characters with a supernatural connection to death, the afterlife, or the undead might be sensed by her.

4. Good Targeting Tactics and Topics
- For Nice Characters: Kyoko’s an icy girl, but also but she won’t push you away if you approach her.
- For Not-So-Nice Characters: DRAMA IS GOOD! Antagonize Kyoko and she’ll give as good as she gets.
- Broken families/found families. Kyoko’s mom is dead. Her dad’s been absent from most of her life (due to being lowkey banned from the family for not being a detective), doesn’t have her respect, and is usually also dead. She’s still coming to grips with the recent discovery that her dad loved her enough to keep her photo in his office and use her name as his wi-fi password. Thus, her only parental figure has been her grandfather (direct predecessor in the Kirigiri line of detectives), and her friends from Hope’s Peak are basically her found family.
- Crazy shit your character has been through if they’ve been through it. Kyoko’s been hunted by a ferris wheel mounted with automatic turrets and watched a dude crash himself into a Denny’s in the same month, and that wasn’t even the most interesting month of her life.

5. Notable Crazy Shit She’s Been Through™
(SPOILERS AHEAD for Danganronpa 1 and Danganronpa Kirigiri!)
- Competed at age 13 in contests known as Duel Noirs, where a shadow organization pulling all the strings would pit a criminal seeking revenge against someone against a detective. The criminal would be allowed to “buy” untracable murder weapons and tricks from the organization, but how much they bought would result in a higher-ranking detective being summoned. The detective’d be given 168 hours to correctly identify the killer or otherwise win if the killer fails to kill their target in time. The summoned detective is protected by the rules against being killed, but this often left Kyoko in harm’s way because it was usually her partner who was actually summoned. Also, the mastermind behid this organization had beef with Grandpa Kirigiri, and he orchestrated the entire thing as a way to prepare to poach Kyoko as his own apprentice and make her into the “Supreme Detective.” He…kind of suceeded?
- At the same time, competed in a contest called Shoot Down the Angel, where she was given a sniper rifle and tasked with disrupting a Duel Noir in progress by rendering the murder impossible while another sniper tries to counter-snipe her and/or ensure the murder proceeds as planned. The guy who organized the contest treated it as just a game, while Kyoko participated because she was promised info that would help her take down the group behind the Duel Noirs.
- Joined up with an art fraud detective she met during the Duel Noirs to hunt down “fallen detectives” across the world who were corrupted by the influence of the guy behind the Duel Noirs.
- Investigated a conspiracy at Hope’s Peak by some of the students to implode the academy and bring about the apocalypse.
- timeline==thh only: Got her memory temproraily wiped, locked in a high school building, and roped into a mutual killing game (Danganronpa) with 14 of her classmates by a psychotic silly bear mascot robot, during which a few of her classmates killed each other. She survived.
- timeline==school only: Got her memory temporarily wiped, locked in a high school building, and roped into gathering supplies and creating several spare bodies for a psychotic silly bear mascot robot by a few of her classmates, with them going off-script every time until the bear got fed up and was about to kill one of them, until the latest imperfect copy they made came to life, beat him up, and made him let everyone leave.

6. Kyoko’s Gloves
- Need a section all of their own. She wears a pair of “black” leather gloves at all times, and usually says as much as she’ll keep them on all game.
- What’s under the gloves? Some nasty burn scars. Why are they there? At age 13, she made an error At age 13, she made a serious error in judgement on a case because of her emotional attachment to one of the prime suspects, her partner at the time, which got her partner killed. Kyoko burned her hands trying to save her partner, but her partner ended up saving her. The burns, the gloves, and her single ribbon are all a tribute to her partner.
- Asking about them is fine, but asking in a shallow or thoughtless way like “You’ve always got those gloves on…” will get a negative reaction out of her. But if that’s how your character would act, drama is good!
- The only characters who can really find out from her what’s under them and why are ones with a similar situation like Dunban or Hanako.
(SPOILERS mostly end here.)

7. Nerdy Variable Nonsense
- Whether her status as the Ultimate Detective is known or not: detectiveReveal is marked if it’s known she is, and careerMention increments by 1 every time she alludes to her detective career.
- timeline marker values: thh if Danganronpa 1 actually happened to her, school if it didn’t.
- Slated to have alternate costumes, so be diligent with your conditions if you want to comment on her clothing (she’ll always wear her gloves all game, and some variant of ribbon to start). Other than the ~kyoko_kirigiri.costume~ variable test, she also has a costume marker that uses a value of 0 for her default outfit.

8. Extra Trivia
- Birthday: October 6, 1993.
- Blood type is B, weight is 48 kg (106 lbs), chest measurement is 82 cm (32”) around.
- Japanese name kanji: 霧切 響子 (Kirigiri Kyouko). Copy+paste into text editor or browser to view characters if they don't render in the CE.

Genuine apologies if you're a foot fetishist here; this is a writing decision based on Kyoko's canon, not my, the writer's, personal attitude towards the kink. She used to be a lot cooler about people being into feet, but then I read Danganronpa Kirigiri Volume 4 and found a description of a 13-year-old Kyoko being asked by adult strangers to take her shoes off for an investigation and her being notably uncomfortable with it. Kitayama Takekuni actually wrote that and made that canon in the Danganronpa universe, because while he is a genius, he is also terrible.

The "is that so" implies quite a bit of subtext that I'm having Kyoko shelf for later. Kyoko considers herself a born detective-- it's the family business and she's been at it since she was like 5-7 years old-- but Miko's words would imply to Kyoko that Miko is calling her entire life and career decisions into question just because Kyoko eagerly took the path that was laid in front of her instead of inventing herself her own way. Kyoko has been surrounded with detectives who went far off the normal courses of their lives to be detectives (particularly her former partner, Yui Samidare), and has a very complicated relationship with her father, who chose NOT to be a detective like the rest of the family and ended up being very absent from her life as a result.
TL;DR: Kyoko is feeling a lot of complicated feelings as a result of Miko saying this and they might come up later.

First things first, the logic for responding to Kyoko is as follows: Just ignore everything in the "Duplicate dialogue" folder and respond to the "Revy-on-Kyoko's-left" cases in the "Inbound stage" folders. Trust me, it'll work itself out.
I spent a long time thinking about this one, and ultimately decided it would be most interesting for Kyoko to just ignore Revy's close-but-not-quite inference and go straight for the trigger discipline issue. I honestly think that by far the most interesting dynamic for Kyoko and Revy to have is one where the former gets on Revy's bad side. Kyoko can come back to the undercover cop thing later.
Feel free to have Revy get absolutely as pissed off about this as you think is appropriate. One of Kyoko's least obvious true character flaws is that, in all her stoicism, she does NOT know when to shut the hell up when someone has a gun, and it has gotten her shot before (in all timelines). Probably not enough for Revy to actually put a bullet between Kyoko's eyes, though...unless you want to pester Richar for a couple of new poses and be prepared to defend that choice from some upset and bewildered fellow devs and feedback reporters.
With Revy, Meia, and Jura more than anyone else, I'm going to try to write targets in a way that'll differentiate Kyoko from Meia as much as I can manage. In this case, this means leaning into Kyoko's willingness to bring up something she deems relevant in a way that shows utter disregard for decorum or the natural flow of conversation-- and, of course, connecting her to Earth stuff. Thanks to the prequel light novels, I now know that Kyoko being alarmingly knowledgable about guns is totally canon.
One last thing: Kyoko is slated to potentially have a costume or too where she isn't wearing a suit of some sort (her Danganronpa S swimwear outfit being most likely; but she may also get an actual non-school uniform suit from The Day Before The Future). We can cross this bridge when we get to it, but if you really want to get crazy about future-proofing now, the condition set I would recommend most is checking for Kyoko having either having school_uniform or formal_attire as a tag.

DUMMY marker condition won't be applied once this case gets fully implemented, I just slapped it on so that this line wouldn't play in actual gameplay yet even as a hidden line. Poses for this line contain assets that haven’t been merged yet, but the first line is set to play with one based on her stern pose (front-facing) and the second is set to play with her rear-facing pose (without eye contact). It's your call whether the first line is appropriate or not, given Rouge in some lines seems to prefer having the player look while the target is too distracted to notice the scope in use.
I’ve decided that Kyoko's gloves are actually valuable enough that they should show up on the scope, what with them being custom-tailored for her hands and made out of some material suitable for touching both dead bodies and everyday objects with. A) this doesn't need a custom pose and B) I don't need to deal with the messy ramifications of the player looking at Kyoko's bare hands, because while she's fine showing conventional chest-and-crotch nudity, there's zero way she'd be cool with that. I would encourage you to have Rouge comment on the potential price point of this purple-peepered poker-playing PI's palm protection (English: value of Kyoko's gloves) to help sell this explanation.
Also, I've made this stage 1 instead of stage 0 because of Kyoko's line about her jacket costing 900 Swiss Francs, which adds up to over a grand in USD (before adjustment from 2010 inflation). If her gloves show up on the scope, then her jacket probably would too. Hope that's alright.
